record_data.record_plain_text: PRELIMINARY STATEMENT Southwest Gas Transmission Company, A Limited Partnership, hereinafter referred to as ¿SGTC,¿ is a ¿natural gas company¿ as defined by the Natural Gas Act (52 Stat. 821, 15 U.S.C. §717¿717w) and, as such, is subject to the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (¿FERC¿). SGTC is engaged in providing a transportation service to Southwest Gas Corporation (¿Southwest¿). The transportation service is undertaken by SGTC only under written contracts acceptable to both Southwest and SGTC and upon the issuance of a certificate of public convenience and necessity by the FERC. SGTC¿s pipeline consists of eight miles of 20-inch O.D. pipe from the northwest one-quarter, Section 17, Township 18 North, Range 21 West; Mohave County, Arizona, to the southern most receipt point of Southwest Gas Corporation¿s Southern Nevada mainline located in the middle of the Colorado River approximately three miles north of the common boundary of Arizona, Nevada and California.

record_data.record_plain_text: STATEMENT OF RATES For Transportation of Natural Gas The rates identified below are applicable to transportation services rendered by SGTC under those executed transportation service agreements with shippers included in SGTC¿s FERC Gas Tariff, Second Revised Volume No. 2, wherein the rates in effect from time to time are indicated to be set forth on this Sheet No. 5. The tariff rates for the services identified below are subject to change from time to time, as may be approved by the FERC, pursuant to a request made by SGTC. The type of transportation services to be rendered, as indicated below, are to be specified by the executed transportation service agreements and the component charge for each type of service so designated and shown below shall apply to the service rendered. Type of Service Effective Rates 1/ 2/ 3/ Mainline Transportation Period I: Rate Schedule T-1 $20,176.24 per month plus $0.01477 per Dth Period II: $17,889.04 per month plus $0.01283 per Dth ________________________ 1/ For the purpose of funding SGTC¿s share of the FERC¿s administration of the natural gas regulatory program, as described in Part 382 of the FERC¿s regulations, this Annual Charge Adjustment (ACA) provision shall be applicable to all rate schedules contained in this tariff. The rates to be charged each month under all rate schedules above shall include a separately identified increment for an ACA unit surcharge. Such surcharge shall be that increment, adjusted to SGTC¿s pressure base and heating value, if required, which is authorized on an annual basis by the FERC. The ACA unit surcharge shall be assessed upon each dekatherm of gas transported by SGTC. The currently effective ACA unit surcharge shall be that which FERC orders to be effective each fiscal year as posted in a notice on its website (HTTP:\\www.ferc.gov) entitled ¿FY [Year] Gas Annual Charges Correction for Annual Charges Unit Charge.¿ The notice period and proposed effective date of filings pursuant to this ACA provision shall be as authorized or ordered by the FERC. Any such filing shall not become effective unless it becomes effective without suspension or refund obligation. SGTC will record annual charges in FERC Account No. 928. Pursuant to Section 154.402(b) of the FERC¿s regulations, SGTC will not attempt to recover any annual charges previously recorded in Account No. 928 in a Natural Gas Act Section 4 rate case. 2/ The Effective Rates will be subject to an annual true-up, which will be calculated by comparing the revenues recovered from the effective rates, without the ACA and other surcharges, for the previous 12 months to the applicable Annual Cost of Service. The first true-up will be applied to the invoice issued 13 months after the effective date of the Period I Rates as a fixed charge or fixed credit. The Period I Annual Cost of Service is $484,230, and the Period II Annual Cost of Service is $429,337. 3/ Period I rates are effective for the first 5 years (60 months) from the effective date of Period I rates. Period II rates are effective thereafter.

record_data.record_plain_text: RATE SCHEDULE T-1 GAS TRANSPORTATION AGREEMENT THIS AGREEMENT is made and entered into as of ____________________(¿Execution Date¿), by and between SOUTHWEST GAS TRANSMISSION COMPANY, A LIMITED PARTNERSHIP, organized in the State of Arizona, hereinafter referred to as ¿SGTC¿, and SOUTHWEST GAS CORPORATION, a California corporation, hereinafter referred to as ¿Shipper.¿ WHEREAS, SGTC owns certain pipeline facilities that it uses to transport natural gas in interstate commerce on behalf of Shipper; WHEREAS, SGTC and Shipper desire to enter into an agreement providing for the transportation by SGTC on behalf of Shipper, pursuant to Section 7 of the Natural Gas Act, of quantities of natural gas owned by Shipper or a third party, from a point of receipt located in Mohave County, Arizona, to a point of delivery located on the boundary between the States of Arizona and Nevada; NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the representations, covenants and conditions herein contained, SGTC and Shipper agree as follows: ARTICLE I Receipt of Natural Gas by SGTC 1.1 Subject to the terms and provisions of this Agreement, SGTC agrees to accept, at the Receipt Points designated pursuant to paragraph 3.1 of Article III, such quantities of natural gas as Shipper may cause to be tendered to SGTC at said points on any day during the term of this Agreement. SGTC hereby agrees that Shipper shall be entitled to the full use of the capacity of SGTC's facilities as necessary to transport natural gas hereunder. ARTICLE II Delivery of Natural Gas by SGTC 2.1 SGTC shall deliver and Shipper shall cause to be accepted each day at the Delivery Point referenced in paragraph 3.2 of Article III, a thermally equivalent quantity of Shipper¿s Natural Gas received by SGTC at the Receipt Points.

record_data.record_plain_text: ARTICLE III Receipt and Delivery Points 3.1 The Receipt Points at which Shipper may cause natural gas to be tendered to SGTC for transportation hereunder are described at Exhibit A to this Agreement. The delivery pressure and actual average atmospheric pressure applicable to such Receipt Points are also set forth at Exhibit A. 3.2 The Delivery Point at which SGTC shall cause to be delivered quantities of Natural Gas transported hereunder is described at Exhibit B to this Agreement. The delivery pressure and actual average atmospheric pressure applicable to such Delivery Point are also set forth at Exhibit B. 3.3 Exhibits A and B, attached to this Agreement, are hereby incorporated by reference as part of this Agreement. The parties may amend Exhibits A or B by mutual agreement, which amendments shall be reflected in a revised Exhibit A or B and shall be incorporated by reference as part of this Agreement. ARTICLE IV Determination of Receipts and Deliveries 4.1 SGTC and Shipper shall exchange information concerning the quantity of Natural Gas received and delivered hereunder in a mutually agreeable manner. 4.2 It is the mutual intent of the parties to this Agreement that the receipt of natural gas by SGTC at the Receipt Points and the delivery by SGTC at the Delivery Point of thermally equivalent quantity of Natural Gas is to be accomplished on a reasonably concurrent basis. However, the parties recognize that operating conditions might, from time to time, cause a temporary and unintentional imbalance between the quantities of Natural Gas that SGTC receives under this Agreement and the quantities of Natural Gas that SGTC delivers under this Agreement. The parties agree to cooperate to eliminate any such imbalances as soon as practicable, but in any event prior to expiration of the term of this Agreement. ARTICLE V Rates and Charges 5.1 Subject to the terms of this Agreement, Shipper agrees to pay SGTC monthly a Monthly Transportation Charge based on SGTC¿s cost of providing the service, plus any other Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (¿FERC¿ or ¿Commission¿) authorized charges, surcharges, and pass-through costs, including but not limited to the Annual Charge Adjustment (¿ACA¿) charge. The Monthly Transportation Charge shall be the rate in effect and reflected from time to time as ¿T-1¿ set forth in SGTC¿s FERC Gas Tariff, Second Revised Volume No. 2, or superseding tariff.

If any change becomes effective on a day other than on the first day of a month, the charge will be prorated accordingly. 5.4 If, in any month, transportation hereunder is interrupted for reasons of force majeure or for alterations and repairs, as provided for by Article VI and Article XI, respectively, of the General Terms and Conditions, the Monthly Transportation Charge payable by Shipper for service hereunder during such month shall be proportionately reduced according to the number of days in such month that transportation is interrupted. ARTICLE VI Facilities 6.1 In the event that it becomes necessary to modify existing facilities or to add additional facilities in order to provide service to shippers of gas other than Shipper, SGTC agrees to provide such modifications or additions at its expense. The Monthly Transportation Charge payable by Shipper under Article V of this Agreement shall not be increased as a result of modifications or additions required because of SGTC¿s desire or obligation to transport any volume of gas for the account of any transportation shipper other than Shipper. 6.2 SGTC is not obligated or required to construct, modify, or rearrange any facilities in order to perform any service, including any facilities necessary to receive gas from, deliver gas to, or measure any gas received from or delivered to any Shipper. In the event SGTC agrees to construct, modify, or rearrange facilities for receipt or delivery of a Shipper¿s gas, SGTC will have the right to condition its agreement to so construct, modify, or rearrange its facilities by requiring that Shipper pay SGTC for the costs associated with the installation, construction, modification and/or rearrangement of such facilities.

record_data.record_plain_text: APPENDIX A GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS 1.Definitions The following terms and expressions, when used in these General Terms and Conditions and in the Gas Transportation Agreement to which these General Terms and Conditions are attached, shall have the following meanings: 1.1 Day ¿ The time period from 9:00 am to 9:00 am Central Clock Time (7:00 am to 7:00 am Pacific Clock Time). 1.2 Month ¿ A period commencing on the first day of the corresponding calendar month and ending on the first day of the next following calendar month. 1.3 Year ¿ A period of three hundred sixty-five (365) consecutive days commencing on the date hereof provided that any such year which contains the date of February 29 shall consist of three hundred sixty-six (366) consecutive days. 1.4 British Thermal Unit (¿Btu¿) ¿ One (1) Btu shall mean one British thermal unit, and is defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one (1) pound of water from fifty-nine degrees Fahrenheit (59°F) to sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60°F) at a constant pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia). Total Btus shall be determined by multiplying the total volume of natural gas delivered times the gas heating value expressed in Btus per cubic foot of gas adjusted on a dry basis. 1.5 Dekatherm (¿Dth¿) ¿ One (1) Dth shall mean one million (1,000,000) Btu¿s. 1.6 Heating Value ¿ The quantity of heat, measured in Btu, produced by combustion in air of one (1) cubic foot of anhydrous gas at a temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60°F) and a constant pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia), the air being at the same temperature and pressure as the gas, after the products of combustion are cooled to the initial temperature of the gas and air, and after condensation of the water formed by combustion.

record_data.record_plain_text: 1.Definitions (Continued) 1.7 Natural Gas ¿ Any mixture of hydrocarbons or of hydrocarbons and noncombustible gases, in a gaseous state, consisting essentially of methane. 1.8 One Thousand Cubic Feet (¿Mcf¿) ¿ The quantity of natural gas occupying a volume of one thousand (1,000) cubic feet at a temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60°F) and at a pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia). 1.9 SGTC System ¿ The natural gas pipeline system that SGTC owns, or will own, as a ¿natural gas company¿ under 15 United States Code, Section 717, et seq., extending from the NW 1/4 of Section 17, Township 18 North, Range 21 West, Mohave County, Arizona, to a point of termination at the boundary between the States of Arizona and Nevada located in the NE 1/4 of Section 9, Township 19 North, Range 22 West, Mohave County, Arizona. 2.Method of Measurement 2.1 Unit of Volume ¿ The unit of volume of gas for all purposes hereunder shall be one (1) Mcf at an absolute pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch (14.73 psia) and at a temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60°F). All readings and registrations of the metering equipment shall be computed into such unit of volume. 2.2 Basis ¿ All ultrasonic meter volumes shall be computed in accordance with the American Gas Association Measurement Committee Report No. 9, including the Appendix thereto, published July 2017, as revised from time to time. Where measurement is by other than ultrasonic meters, all necessary factors for proper volume determination shall be applied. All ultrasonic meter volumes shall be corrected for deviations from the ideal gas laws (supercompressibility) in accordance with the referenced Committee Report No. 9. For the purpose of measurement, the atmospheric pressure shall be the actual average atmospheric pressure specified in this Agreement.
record_data.filing_title: Prefile Settlement in Lieu of Rate Filling

record_data.record_plain_text: 2.Method of Measurement (Continued) 2.3 Determination of Heating Value ¿ The daily average heating value of gas shall be determined by analysis of samples obtained from continuous sampling devices by SGTC or its upstream suppliers. The samples shall be run on a recording calorimeter or chromatograph, employing the Thomas principle of calorimetry, or by means of some other recognized method, located as near the Receipt Points as practicable. The heating value of the natural gas delivered to Shipper will depend upon the source of the supplies. The average heating values will be determined from the volumetric weighted average heating values of the supplies being delivered into SGTC. Billing period heating values shall be the arithmetic average of the heating values as determined above for each day during such period. 2.4 Determination of Flowing Temperature ¿ The temperature of the gas flowing through a meter station shall be obtained daily by the use of a recording thermometer located at the measuring station. The arithmetic average temperature of the gas during the chart period shall be used in computing the delivery of gas during such period. 2.5 Determination of Specific Gravity ¿ The specific gravity shall be determined by means of a recording gravitometer or other recognized method by SGTC or its upstream suppliers at a location as near the Receipt Points as practicable. The specific gravity of the natural gas delivered to Shipper will depend upon the source of the supplies. The average specific gravity will be determined from the volumetric weighted average specific gravity values of the supplies being delivered into SGTC. Billing period specific gravities shall be the arithmetic average of the specific gravities as determined above for each day during such period. 2.6 Chromatographic Analysis ¿ If the daily average heating value and/or the daily average specific gravity is determined by chromatographic analysis of the gas sample, the values of the physical constants for the gas compounds and the procedure for determining the gross heating value and/or the specific gravity of the gas from them shall be in accordance with applicable American Gas Association Committee reports. 3.Measuring Equipment 3.1 Installation and Operation ¿ It is the intent of the parties to utilize measuring facilities to be located near the Receipt Points to measure the volume of gas delivered hereunder for purposes of this Agreement. The measuring facilities are, or shall be, owned by SGTC. Where used, ultrasonic meters shall be installed and operated in accordance with American Gas Association Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 9, as revised from time to time. If turbine meters are used, they shall be installed and operated in accordance with American Gas Association Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 7, as revised from time to time.
record_data.filing_title: Prefile Settlement in Lieu of Rate Filling

record_data.record_plain_text: 3.Measuring Equipment (Continued) 3.2 Installation and Operation by Shipper ¿ Shipper may install, maintain and operate at its own expense, at the Receipt and Delivery Points, check meters and other necessary equipment by which the volume of gas delivered may be measured. If orifice meters are used, they shall employ flange taps and shall be installed and operated in accordance with the American Gas Association Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 3, as revised from time to time. If turbine meters are used, they shall be installed and operated in accordance with American Gas Association Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 7, as revised from time to time. If ultrasonic meters are used, they shall be installed and operated in accordance with the American Gas Association Transmission Measurement Committee Report No. 9, as revised from time to time. 3.3 Non-interference ¿ Measuring equipment applying to or affecting deliveries shall be installed in such manner as to permit an accurate determination of the quantity of gas delivered and ready verification of the accuracy of measurement. The parties shall exercise care in the installation, maintenance and operation of pressure regulating equipment or gas compressors so as to prevent any inaccuracy in the determination of the volume of gas being measured. 3.4 Calibration and Test of and Access to Meters ¿ Each party shall have the right to have representatives present at the time of any installing, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, testing, calibrating or adjusting done in connection with the other party's measuring equipment, including calorimeters, used in the measurement of deliveries of gas. The accuracy of the measuring equipment, including calorimeters, shall be verified at reasonable intervals but not more frequently than once in any thirty (30) day period. In the event either party shall notify the other that it desires a special test of said measuring equipment or of the check measuring equipment, as the case may be, the parties shall cooperate to secure prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment. Each party shall give to the other party sufficient advance notice of the time of all such special tests so that the other party may conveniently have its representatives present. 3.5 Records ¿ Upon request of either party, the other shall submit the records from its measuring equipment used in the measurement and billing of gas hereunder, together with calculations therefrom, for inspection and verification, subject to return within thirty (30) days after receipt. The parties shall preserve all test data, and other required data pertaining to the measurement of gas by their respective measurement equipment for a period of three (3) years or such other period or periods as may be prescribed with respect to them by regulatory bodies having jurisdiction.
record_data.filing_title: Prefile Settlement in Lieu of Rate Filling

record_data.record_plain_text: 3.Measuring Equipment (Continued) 3.6 Correction of Metering Errors ¿ If, upon test, the measuring equipment is found to be in error by not more than two percent (2%), previous recordings of such equipment shall be considered accurate in computing deliveries, but such equipment shall be adjusted at once to record accurately. If, upon test, the measuring equipment shall be found to be inaccurate by an amount exceeding two percent (2%), at a recording corresponding to the average hourly rate of flow for the period since the last preceding test, then any previous recordings of such equipment shall be corrected to zero error for any period that is known definitely or agreed upon. In case the period is not known or agreed upon, such correction shall be for a period equal to the lesser of one-half of the time elapsed since the date of the last test or sixteen (16) days. 3.7 Failure of Meters ¿ In the event a meter is out of service or registering inaccurately, the volume of gas delivered shall be determined: (i)By correcting the error if the percentage of error isascertainable by calibration, test or mathematicalcalculations; or in the absence of (i), then (ii)By using the registration of any check meter or meters, ifinstalled and accurately registering; or in the absence ofboth (i) and (ii), then (iii)By estimating the quantity of delivery during periods undersimilar conditions when the meter was registering accurately. 3.8 Access to Measuring Equipment ¿ Whenever any point of delivery provided for is on the premises of one party, the other party shall have the right of free use and ingress and egress at all reasonable times for the purpose of installation, operation, repair or removal of measuring equipment. In the event check measuring equipment is installed, the other party shall have access to the same at all reasonable times, but the reading, calibration and adjusting thereof shall be done only by the party installing the check measuring equipment.

record_data.record_plain_text: 4.Quality 4.1 All Natural Gas delivered to SGTC at the Receipt Points and caused to be delivered by SGTC at the Delivery Point shall conform to the following specifications: (i) Oxygen ¿ The gas shall not at any time have an oxygen content in excess of two-tenths of one percent (0.2%) and every reasonable effort shall be made to keep the gas tendered free of oxygen. (ii) Liquids ¿ The gas shall be free of water and hydrocarbons in liquid form at the temperature and pressure at which the gas is delivered. The gas shall in no event contain water vapor in excess of seven (7) pounds per million cubic feet. (iii) Hydrogen Sulfide ¿ The gas shall not contain more than one-quarter (1/4) grain of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) cubic feet. (iv) Total Sulfur ¿ The gas shall not contain more than five (5) grains of total sulfur per one hundred (100) cubic feet. (v) Carbon Dioxide ¿ The gas shall not have a carbon dioxide content in excess of one percent (1%) by volume. (vi) Dust, Gums and Solid Matter ¿ The gas shall be commercially free of dust, gums and other solid matter. (vii) Heating Value ¿ The gas shall contain a daily average heating content of not less than nine hundred seventy-five (975) Btu's per cubic foot. (viii) Temperature ¿ The gas shall be delivered at temperatures not in excess of one hundred twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120°F). 4.2 SGTC agrees to deliver gas to Shipper which shall not contain any toxic or hazardous substance in concentrations which, in the normal use of the gas, may be hazardous to health, injurious to pipeline facilities, or be a limit to merchantability or be contrary to applicable government standards. 4.3 If, at any time, gas tendered for delivery shall fail to substantially conform to any of the quality specifications set forth in paragraph 4.1 above or with the provisions of paragraph 4.2 above and the receiving party notifies the delivering party of such deficiency and the delivering party fails to remedy any such deficiency within a reasonable period of time, the receiving party may, at its option, refuse to accept delivery pending correction of the deficiency by the delivering party or continue to accept delivery and make such changes necessary to cause the gas to conform to such specifications, in which event the delivering party shall reimburse the receiving party for all reasonable expenses incurred by the receiving party in effecting such changes. Nothing in this paragraph 4.3 shall be construed to eliminate, or limit in any manner, the rights and obligations existing under any other provisions of this Agreement.
record_data.filing_title: Prefile Settlement in Lieu of Rate Filling

record_data.record_plain_text: 5.Billing and Payment 5.1 Billing ¿ On or before the fifteenth (15th) day of each month SGTCshall provide to Shipper an invoice evidencing the bill for services rendered to Shipper under this Agreement during the preceding month. When Shipper is in control of information required by SGTC to prepare invoices, Shipper shall cause such information to be received by SGTC on or before the tenth (10th) day of the month immediately following the month to which the information applies. 5.2 Payment ¿ Payment to SGTC for services rendered during the preceding month shall be due on the twenty-sixth (26th) day of the calendar month next succeeding that month for which such service was rendered and shall be paid by Shipper on or before such due date. Alternative forms of payment, alternative due dates, and alternative payment schedules will be accepted upon mutual agreement of the Parties. 5.3 Delayed Bill ¿ If SGTC fails to provide any bill by the fifteenth (15th) day of the month, then the time of payment shall be extended by one (1)day for each day that the provision of said bill is delayed unlessShipper is responsible for such delay, or unless alternative due dates orpayment schedules have been mutually agreed to by the Parties. 5.4 Failure to Pay Bills ¿ Should Shipper fail to pay all of the amount of any bill when the same becomes due, SGTC may send Shipper a late unpaid balance notice. In the event Shipper does not pay the unpaid balance within seven (7) calendar days of transmission of the late unpaid balance notice, SGTC may assess a late charge on the unpaid balance that shall accrue on each calendar day from the due date using the interest rates and procedures specified in Section 154.501(d) of the Commission¿s regulations as amended from time to time. If either principal or late charges are due, any payments thereafter received shall first be applied to the late charge due, then to the previously outstanding principal due and, lastly, to the most current principal due. Subject to requirements of regulatory bodies having jurisdiction and without prejudice to any other rights and remedies available to SGTC under the law and this Agreement, SGTC shall have the right to discontinue transportation service hereunder if any bill remains unpaid for thirty (30) days after the due date thereof or if Shipper breaches any of the other terms and conditions of this Agreement and, for thirty (30) days after receipt of written notice from SGTC of such other breach, fails to remedy or correct the same; provided, however, that in the event of a bona fide dispute between the parties in respect of breach, or in respect of the amount due under any bill, SGTC shall not have the right to discontinue the transportation of gas hereunder for Shipper's account until after the expiration of thirty (30) days from the date of final decision no longer subject to appeal by a court of competent jurisdiction, and not then, unless the decision of the court has determined such dispute in favor of SGTC and against Shipper and Shipper has failed to remedy or correct such violation or breach of contract within said thirty (30) day period. Transportation of gas shall be resumed upon remedy of Shipper's breach.

record_data.record_plain_text: 5.Billing and Payment(Continued) 5.5 Adjustment of Errors ¿ In the event an error is discovered in any invoice that SGTC renders, such error shall be adjusted within thirty (30) days of the determination thereof; provided, however, that any claim for adjustment must be made within twelve (12) months from the date of such invoice. 6.Force Majeure 6.1 Effect of Force Majeure ¿ In the event of either SGTC or Shipper being rendered unable by force majeure to wholly or in part carry out its obligations under the provisions of this Agreement, it is agreed that the obligations of the party affected by such force majeure, other than to make payments then due hereunder, shall be suspended without liability for breach of contract during the continuance of any inability so caused but for no longer period, and such cause shall, so far as possible, be remedied with all reasonable dispatch. A force majeure event affecting the performance by either party hereunder shall not relieve it of liability in the event of its concurring negligence, where such negligence was a cause of the force majeure event, or in the event of its failure to use reasonable diligence to remedy the situation and remove the cause in an adequate manner and with all reasonable dispatch, nor shall such causes or contingencies relieve either party of liability unless such party shall give notice and full particulars of the same in writing to the other party as soon as possible after the occurrence relied on. 6.2 Definition of Force Majeure ¿ The term amp;force majeureamp; as employed herein shall mean acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, failure of any third parties necessary to the performance by either SGTC or Shipper under this Agreement, inability to obtain pipe or other material or equipment or labor, wars, riots, insurrections, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, washouts, arrests and restraint of rulers and people, interruptions by government or court orders, present or future orders of any regulatory body having proper jurisdiction, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe, freezing of wells or pipelines, and any other cause whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not within the control of the party claiming suspension and which, by the exercise of due diligence, such party is unable to overcome. Nothing contained herein, however, shall be construed to require either party to settle a strike against its will. 7.Control and Possession of Natural Gas 7.1 As between SGTC and Shipper, SGTC shall be deemed to be in control and possession of the natural gas from the time it is delivered to SGTC at the Receipt Points until it is redelivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point, and Shipper shall be deemed to be in control and possession of the natural gas at all other times.

record_data.record_plain_text: 8.Adverse Claims to Natural Gas 8.1 Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold harmless SGTC, its officers, agents, employees and contractors against any liability, loss or damage whatsoever, including costs and attorneys' fees, suffered by SGTC, its officers, agents, employees or contractors, where such liability, loss or damage arises directly or indirectly out of any demand, claim, action, cause of action or suit brought by any person, association or entity, public or private, asserting ownership of or an interest in the natural gas tendered for transportation hereunder. 9.Odorization 9.1 As between SGTC and Shipper, SGTC shall have no obligation whatsoever to odorize the natural gas delivered hereunder, nor to maintain any odorant levels in such natural gas. SGTC will grant Shipper access to SGTC¿s facilities near the Receipt Points to enable Shipper to install facilities to odorize the natural gas entering SGTC¿s facilities. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold harmless SGTC, its officers, agents, employees and contractors against any liability, loss or damage, including costs and attorneys' fees, whether or not such liability, loss or damage arises out of any demand, claim, action, cause of action, and/or suit brought by Shipper or by any person, association or entity, public or private, that is not a party to this Agreement, where such liability, loss or damage is suffered by SGTC, its officers, agents, employees and/or contractors as a direct or indirect result of any actual or alleged failure by Shipper, SGTC and/or any other person, association, or entity, public or private, to odorize the natural gas or product delivered hereunder or to maintain any odorant levels in such natural gas or product. 10.Non-Waiver for Future Default 10.1 No waiver by either SGTC or Shipper of any one or more defaults bythe other in performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement shall operate or be construed as a waiver of any other existing or future default or defaults, whether of a like or of a different character. 11.Service Conditions 11.1 Alterations and Repairs ¿ SGTC shall have the right, withoutliability to Shipper, to interrupt the transportation of natural gas when necessary to test, alter, modify, enlarge or repair any facility or property comprising a part of, or appurtenant to, the SGTC system, or otherwise related to the operation thereof. SGTC shall endeavor to cause a minimum of inconvenience to Shipper and, except in cases of emergency, shall give Shipper advance notice of its intention to so interrupt the transportation of gas and of the expected magnitude of such interruptions.

record_data.record_plain_text: 12.Statutory Regulation 12.1 The respective obligations of SGTC and Shipper under this Agreement are subject to the laws, orders, rules and regulations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction. 13.Descriptive Headings 13.1 The descriptive headings of the provisions of this Agreement and of these General Terms and Conditions are formulated and used for convenience only and shall not be deemed to affect the meaning or construction of any such provision. 14.Law Applicable 14.1 SGTC and Shipper expressly agree that the laws of the State of Arizona shall govern the validity, construction, interpretation and effect of this Agreement and of these General Terms and Conditions. 15.Taxes 15.1 Shipper shall pay or cause to be paid all taxes and assessments imposed on Shipper with respect to natural gas transported hereunder prior to and including its delivery to SGTC, and SGTC shall pay or cause to be paid all taxes and assessments imposed on SGTC with respect to natural gas transported hereunder after its receipt by SGTC and prior to redelivery to Shipper, provided, however, that Shipper shall pay to SGTC all taxes, levies or charges which SGTC may by law be required to collect from Shipper by reasons of all services performed for Shipper hereunder. 15.2 Neither party shall be responsible or liable for any taxes or other statutory charges levied or assessed against any of the facilities of the other party used for the purpose of carrying out the provisions of this Agreement. 16.Charges, Penalties, and Cash Outs 16.1 Shipper shall reimburse SGTC for any penalties or cash outs for imbalance management from any Transporter delivering gas that may be assessed to SGTC by any transporters delivering gas into the SGTC System. SGTC shall provide prompt notice to Shipper whenever any transporter delivering gas into the SGTC System notifies SGTC that a penalty has been incurred or that SGTC is in danger of incurring a penalty. If SGTC were to receive a cash-out payment from any Transporter delivering gas into the SGTC system as a result of imbalance management, SGTC will provide a credit in that amount to Shipper on its invoice.
